Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1106–10 October 1141":"1106–10 October 1141","1104–1169":"1104–1169","1106–1141":"1106–1141","1108–Male":"1108–Deceased","1094–1148":"1094–1148","1138–1201":"1138–1201","1141–1186":"1141–1186","1065–1130":"1065–1130","1081–1150":"1081–1150","10 October 1141":"10 October 1141","1065":"1065","1186":"1186","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1094":"1094","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","Bef 1130":"before 1130","1138":"1138","1148":"1148","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1108":"1108","Thorngate Castle, Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","Coventry, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Condet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Condover (Shropshire), earlier recorded as <i>Conedovre</i> and <i>Conedor'</i>.","English: in northern England perhaps a variant of   Connor   with intrusive <i>-d-</i>.","Possibly an Americanized form of German   Kanter   or   Ganter  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Condor","meanings":["English: variant of   Conder  .","Altered form of Hungarian   Kondor  . This form of the surname is also found in Romania.","Amerindian and Spanish (<b>Cóndor</b>): from <i>cóndor</i>, a word of Quechuan origin, documented in Spain since the 16th century."]},{"name":"Connor","meanings":["Irish and Manx: shortened form of   O'Connor  , which is an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Conchobhair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Conchobhar</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":0,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Condet Lord of Thorngate was born in 1106, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Osbert de Cundy, was 42 and his mother, Adelaide Chesney, was 25. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Alice De Gernon Countess Of Hertford. He died on 10 October 1141, in his hometown, a